{"questionId":"9076557","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>An ohmic conductor is connected to an ideal ammeter and to a power supply of output voltage V.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"https://ib-questionbank-attachments.s3.amazonaws.com/uploads/tinymce_asset/asset/4686/Schermafbeelding_2018-08-10_om_17.57.33.png\" alt=\"M18/4/PHYSI/SP2/ENG/TZ1/04\"></p>\n<p>The following data are available for the conductor:</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; density of free electrons&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;= 8.5 × 10<sup>22</sup>&nbsp;cm<sup>−3</sup></p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; resistivity&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ρ =&nbsp;1.7 × 10<sup>−8</sup>&nbsp;Ωm</p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; dimensions&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;w&nbsp;× h&nbsp;× l = 0.020 cm × 0.020 cm × 10 cm.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The ammeter reading is 2.0 A.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The electric field <em>E </em>inside the sample can be approximated as the uniform electric field between two parallel plates.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{v}{E} = \\frac{1}{{ne\\rho }}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>v</mi>\n    <mi>E</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mrow>\n      <mi>n</mi>\n      <mi>e</mi>\n      <mi>ρ</mi>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong><em>ALTERNATIVE 1</em></strong></p>\n<p>clear use of Ohm’s Law (<em>V&nbsp;</em>=&nbsp;<em>IR</em>)</p>\n<p>clear use of <em>R</em>&nbsp;= <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{\\rho L}}{A}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mi>ρ</mi>\n      <mi>L</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mi>A</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span></p>\n<p>combining with <em>I </em>= <em>nAve </em>and <em>V </em>= <em>EL </em>to reach result.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong><em>ALTERNATIVE 2</em></strong></p>\n<p>attempts to substitute values into equation.</p>\n<p>correctly calculates LHS as 4.3 × 10<sup>9</sup>.</p>\n<p>correctly calculates RHS as 4.3 × 10<sup>9</sup>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong><em>For ALTERNATIVE 1 look for:</em></strong></p>\n<p><em>V</em> =&nbsp;<em>IR</em></p>\n<p><em>R</em> =&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{\\rho L}}{A}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mi>ρ</mi>\n      <mi>L</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mi>A</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span></p>\n<p><em>V</em> =&nbsp;<em>EL</em></p>\n<p><em>I</em> =&nbsp;<em>nAve</em></p>\n<p><em>V</em> =&nbsp;<em>I</em><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{\\rho L}}{A}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mi>ρ</mi>\n      <mi>L</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mi>A</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span></p>\n<p><em>EL</em> = <em>I</em><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{\\rho L}}{A}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mi>ρ</mi>\n      <mi>L</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mi>A</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span></p>\n<p><em>E</em> =&nbsp;<em>I</em><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{\\rho }{A}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>ρ</mi>\n    <mi>A</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span></p>\n<p><em>E</em> =&nbsp;<em>nAve</em><em><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{\\rho }{A}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>ρ</mi>\n    <mi>A</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span> = nveρ</em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{v}{E} = \\frac{1}{{ne\\rho }}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>v</mi>\n    <mi>E</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mrow>\n      <mi>n</mi>\n      <mi>e</mi>\n      <mi>ρ</mi>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span></p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9076557","referenceCode":"18M.2.HL.TZ1.4c.ii","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Show that v E = 1 n e ρ .","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 5: Electricity and magnetism","5.1 – Electric fields","Core","Topic 5: Electricity and magnetism"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}